Date: Sat 15 Mar 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Reforma (Mexico), Sat 8 Mar 2003 (translated by Maria Jacobs,
ProMED-ESP) [edited]
<http://www.reforma.com/nacional/articulo/275915/default.htm>

Mexico: West Nile Virus-infected Birds Found in Nuevo Laredo
------------------------------------------------------------
MONTERREY: State health authorities have confirmed the presence of West
Nile virus [WNV] in Nuevo Leon, Mexico, after samples from 3 birds in a
ranch in the municipality of Lampazos yielded positive results.
[By Jose Garcia and Cesar Cepeda]
******
[2]
Date: Sat 15 Mar 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: El Norte (Mexico), Fri 14 Mar 2003 (translated by Maria Jacobs,
ProMED-ESP) [edited]
<http://www.elnorte.com/parseo/busquedas.asp?tex=virus&pagetoprint=../monterrey/articulo/292363/default.htm>

Mexico: West Nile Virus Alert Extended to Include Four Other Municipalities
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
MONTERREY: Yesterday, the West Nile virus alert was extended to include
several municipalities. Thirteen dead birds found in the municipalities of
San Pedro (6 found in a park and in the yards of two homes), Pesqueria (4),
Los Aldamas (2), and Marin (1) were sent to the Health Department for
confirmation of the presence of West Nile virus infection.
Laura Lopez Sanchez, head of the VI Health Jurisdiction, stated yesterday
that the possible presence of West Nile virus is being investigated in
those localities, and that the results of laboratory tests will be
available in one week.
******
[3]
Date: Sat 15 Mar 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: El Norte (Mexico), Fri 14 Mar 2003 (translated by Maria Jacobs,
ProMED-ESP) [edited]
<http://www.elnorte.com/parseo/busquedas.asp?tex=virus&pagetoprint=../nacional/articulo/292416/default.htm>

Mexico: West Nile Virus Confirmed at Tamaulipas Border
------------------------------------------------------
MEXICO CITY: Luis Mar Serrano, head of Epidemiology for the IV Sanitary
Jurisdiction of the Health Department, confirmed that federal health
authorities have detected West Nile virus at the border of the state of
Tamaulipas. Residents of the area have been advised to report the presence
of mosquito breeding sites.
Serrano stated that this region is under alert and that INRE has confirmed
the presence of West Nile virus in the area. The health department is in
contact with the Department of Agriculture, Rural Development, Fisheries,
and Food Industry (Sagarpa), veterinarians, and farmers, and together, they
are carrying out constant epidemiological surveillance.
The laboratory results from 4 patients with meningitis, one of whom died,
are still pending.
[Byline: Miguel Dominguez and Efrain Klerigan]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is the first report of West Nile virus-positive dead birds in the
Americas this year. It is presumed that as in the first report above the
presence of West Nile virus has been confirmed in dead birds only. Further
information is requested from the relevant authorities regarding the nature
of the tests carried out on the dead birds, and the outcome of
investigation of the suspected human cases. - Mod.CP]
